{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:28:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:28:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14695"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14695"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.06,0.2,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111787"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93857"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2665"},{"type":"tags","id":"4510"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45752"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111787"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with increasing shortness of breath on exertion over six months. She has a history of rheumatic fever in childhood. She takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse is irregularly irregular at 90/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a mid-diastolic murmur at the apex. An electrocardiogram confirms atrial fibrillation. Transthoracic echocardiogram shows mitral valve area of 1.3 cm\u00b2 (mitral stenosis) with mean pressure gradient of 7 mmHg across the valve.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate anticoagulation strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warfarin","Rivaroxaban","Apixaban","Dabigatran","Low molecular weight heparin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with moderate mitral stenosis (mitral valve area 1.3 cm\u00b2) and atrial fibrillation. The combination significantly increases the risk of thromboembolism, necessitating anticoagulation. The stenosis is likely due to previous rheumatic heart disease, which remains the most common cause worldwide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice for anticoagulation in this scenario. It is the only anticoagulant that has been extensively studied and proven effective in patients with moderate to severe mitral stenosis and atrial fibrillation. The target International Normalised Ratio (INR) should be maintained between 2.0-3.0.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Edabigatran\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Erivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E are direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) that are contraindicated in moderate to severe mitral stenosis. While these agents are often preferred over warfarin in non-valvular atrial fibrillation due to their more predictable pharmacokinetics and reduced need for monitoring, they have not been adequately studied in patients with significant mitral stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow molecular weight heparin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate as a bridge to therapeutic warfarin or perioperatively, but it is not suitable for long-term anticoagulation in this ambulatory patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe severity of mitral stenosis is classified based on valve area: mild (\u0026gt;1.5 cm\u00b2), moderate (1.1-1.5 cm\u00b2), and severe (\u0026lt;1.0 cm\u00b2). A mean pressure gradient \u0026gt;5 mmHg across the mitral valve suggests haemodynamically significant stenosis. This patient\u0027s symptoms and echo parameters are consistent with moderate mitral stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Warfarin is preferred over direct oral anticoagulants in patients with moderate to severe mitral stenosis and atrial fibrillation.","Mitral valve area of 1.1-1.5 cm\u00b2 indicates moderate mitral stenosis.","Mean pressure gradient \u003E5 mmHg across the mitral valve suggests haemodynamically significant stenosis."],"references":["2024 ESC Guidelines for the management of atrial fibrillation developed in collaboration with the European Association for Cardio-Thoracic Surgery (EACTS)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93857"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14695"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93857"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T21:24:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T21:24:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111787"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"